==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wan
<hw>Wan</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <mark>obs.</mark> <pos>imp.</pos> of
<er>Win</er>. <def>Won.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wan</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wan
<hw>Wan</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>wann</ets>,
<ets>wonn</ets>, <ets>wan</ets>, <ets>won</ets>, dark, lurid, livid,
perhaps originally, worn out by toil, from <ets>winnan</ets> to labor,
strive. See <er>Win</er>.]</ety> <def>Having a pale or sickly hue;
languid of look; pale; pallid.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Sad to view, his visage pale
and <xex>wan</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My color . . . [is] <qex>wan</qex> and of a leaden hue.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Why so pale and <qex>wan</qex>, fond lover?</q>
<rj><qau>Suckling.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With the <qex>wan</qex> moon overhead.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wan</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Wan
<hw>Wan</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality of being wan;
wanness.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Tinged with <qex>wan</qex> from lack of sleep.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wan</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Wan
<hw>Wan</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To grow wan; to become
pale or sickly in looks.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧All his visage
<xex>wanned</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And ever he mutter'd and madden'd, and ever <qex>wann'd</qex> with
despair.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wand</ent>⟦br⟧
